  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] ▦ : '
    value: 曰
english:
  title: Preface for the Great Treasury Scriptures Dharma Hall
  author: Choe Hong-yun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When the elephant bore the Dharma wheel and the dragon embraced the Bodhi tree, upon the Monkey River was revealed the true source of the nature-water, and within the Parrot Garden were plucked all the finest fruits of the Buddhist forest. Yet when the Tathagata entered into perfect extinction, the true teaching grew slack and fell into decline. The Master Zhiyan, analyzing the dust of phenomena, illuminated the profound principles of the Expanded Teachings. The Master Dignaga, rebuking the very stones, compiled the doctrines of Yoga that correspond to all things. Some, like Master Zongmi, pointed with his hand to the yellow flowers and scattered the dew of wisdom upon the streams of Caoqi. Others, like Master Xiang, caused white sand to spring forth from his words and spread clouds of compassion upon the peaks of Tiantai. Master Xiaogong deepened the ocean of the Fenshuang tradition's teachings, their currents reaching all the ten directions. The Master Fazang, expounding the precious jewels of the Vairocana precepts, extended his benefits throughout the three realms. Though the Chan and doctrinal schools may seem distinct, the nature and characteristics have never truly diverged. Should one earnestly and reverently turn toward the supreme refuge, one shall immediately obtain boundless benefits.

    Considering my humble and unworthy self, undeserving to inherit this great throne, I hold fast to reverence for the mandate of heaven, finding no ease day or night, as though bearing the burden of the house of Yin. From dawn until dusk I take no food, yet still harbor the concerns of the Zhou sovereigns. And now, as heaven's reproach rests upon this body, the stars have repeatedly strayed from their courses. The great moon has entered the mansion of golden Taurus, and the planet of the year encroaches upon the palace of the great crab. The calamities afflicting the realm are difficult to remedy by human effort alone. Only through the protection of Buddha and the spirits can we restore harmony to the times.

    With sincere reverence, I have specially arranged this lecture platform and gathered the enlightened monks from the Vulture Peak. We recite and proclaim the magnificent doctrines from the profound treasures. As the jade whisk stirs the wind, we comprehend the sublime subtlety of the Master Uicheon. As the moon rests in the jade vessel, we attain the clarity and brilliance of the wisdom mirror.

    I humbly pray that swift spiritual blessings may descend, and the shade of boundless wisdom may shelter us. May seven hundred years pass without blemish or breaking, that this body may dwell in goodness. May the sovereign enjoy the blessings of longevity and well-being, ruling the realm through countless ages.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Monkey River and Parrot Garden are classical Buddhist allusions to places where the Buddha's teachings were revealed.
  - key: ''
    value: Zhiyan, Dignaga, Zongmi, Xiang, Xiaogong, and Fazang are renowned Buddhist masters whose teachings are referenced here.
  - key: ''
    value: Caoqi refers to the lineage of Huineng, the Sixth Patriarch; Tiantai refers to the mountain seat of that school of Buddhism.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Vulture Peak' alludes to the place where the Buddha delivered the Lotus Sutra.
  - key: ''
    value: Master Uicheon (義天) was a renowned Korean Buddhist scholar and reformer of the Goryeo period.
  - key: ''
    value: The celestial anomalies mentioned (the moon's irregular position, planetary disruptions) were interpreted in East Asian thought as signs of cosmic disorder reflecting earthly misrule.
